{{Nihon no hō}}
'''Ryō no Gige''' (令義解) is an interpretive text of the {{ill|Yōrō Code|ja|養老令|12=draft|12=draft}}, created to establish precise guidelines<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|和書|title=令義解 凡例|year=1939|publisher=新訂増補 国史大系 第22巻|page=1|author=黒板|url=https://dl.ndl.go.jp/pid/3431635/1/108}}</ref>. It was compiled in 833 CE ({{ill|Tenchō|ja|天長|12=draft|12=draft}} 10) under an imperial edict from Emperor Junna, with the right minister {{ill|Kiyohara no Natsuno|ja|清原夏野|12=draft|12=draft}} serving as chief editor. The compilation involved 12 notable scholars, including {{ill|Sugawara no Kiyotomo|ja|菅原清公|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Sanuki no Emanari|ja|讃岐永直|12=draft|12=draft}}, and others<ref>{{Cite book|和書|title=令義解序|publisher= |series=新訂増補 国史大系|volume=第22|url=https://dl.ndl.go.jp/pid/3431635/1/118|author=黒板}}</ref>. The work originally comprised 30 articles across 10 volumes<ref name=":0" />, but only 21 articles remain extant. Seven of these can be extracted from the {{ill|Ryōshū Gige|ja|令集解|12=draft|12=draft}}, and additional fragments of two articles have been collected since the early modern period. Modern editions, including those from the {{ill|National Historical Series|ja|国史大系|12=draft|12=draft}}, incorporate these reconstructed texts.

Since the {{ill|Yōrō Code|ja|養老令|12=draft|12=draft}} has been lost, the ''Ryō no Gige'' serves as a critical source for the transmission of both the {{ill|Taihō Code|ja|大宝律令|12=draft|12=draft}} and the Yōrō Code<ref name=":0" />. Unlike the ''{{ill|Ryōshū Gige|ja|令集解|12=draft|12=draft}}'', a private commentary compiled by {{ill|Wemune Naomoto|ja|惟宗直本|12=draft|12=draft}}, the ''Ryō no Gige'' was an officially sanctioned commentary with legal authority.

The structure of the text presents the original law in bold characters, with the interpretive commentary added in smaller, double-spaced text between the lines.

== Compilers ==
